(304,	0,	30,	20251007,	'ai',	'Okay, my apologies for the cut-off response! I will continue and complete the information regarding the **Subclass 482 Temporary Skill Shortage (TSS) visa**.\n\n---\n\n### Subclass 482 Temporary Skill Shortage (TSS) Visa (Australia) - Continued\n\n#### Key Features and Requirements (General):\n\n**For the Employer (Sponsor):**\n\n*   **Standard Business Sponsorship (SBS):** The employer must be approved as a standard business sponsor. This involves demonstrating that the business is lawfully operating, has a good training record (or an exemption applies), and meets other sponsorship obligations.\n*   **Nomination:** The employer must nominate an eligible skilled position within their business. This involves:\n    *   Demonstrating a genuine need for an overseas worker.\n    *   Showing that they have tried to recruit an Australian worker (Labour Market Testing - LMT) unless an exemption applies.\n    *   Ensuring the position\'s terms and conditions are no less favourable than those for an Australian worker.\n    *   **Paying the Skilling Australians Fund (SAF) levy:** This is a training levy paid by the employer at the time of nomination, calculated based on the business\'s annual turnover and the visa duration.\n    *   The nominated occupation must be on the relevant skilled occupation list for the chosen stream (STSOL or MLTSSL).\n\n**For the Visa Applicant (Employee):**\n\n*   **Occupation and Skills:** The applicant must have skills, qualifications, and employment background that match the nominated occupation. This often involves providing evidence of qualifications, work experience, and sometimes skills assessments.\n*   **English Language Proficiency:** Applicants must meet specific English language requirements unless an exemption applies (e.g., citizenship of certain countries, completion of certain studies). Requirements vary by stream.\n*   **Health and Character:** All applicants and their accompanying family members must meet Australia\'s health and character requirements.\n*   **Genuine Temporary Entrant (GTE):** While not a direct requirement for the 482 visa, applicants must genuinely intend to perform the nominated occupation.\n*   **Age:** There is generally no age limit for the 482 visa, unlike some permanent visa categories.\n*   **Employer-Sponsored:** You cannot apply for this visa independently; you must be sponsored by an approved Australian employer.\n\n---\n\n#### Streams and Duration:\n\n1.  **Short-term stream:**\n    *   For occupations on the **Short-term Skilled Occupation List (STSOL)**.\n    *   Generally granted for up to **2 years** (or up to 4 years if an International Trade Obligation applies).\n    *   Can usually be renewed once onshore, subject to meeting criteria.\n    *   Typically does **not** provide a direct pathway to permanent residency, though pathways may exist via other visas or a different 482 stream.\n\n2.  **Medium-term stream:**\n    *   For occupations on the **Medium and Long-term Strategic Skills List (MLTSSL)** or a Regional Occupation List.\n    *   Generally granted for up to **4 years**.\n    *   Can be renewed multiple times.\n    *   Provides a **pathway to permanent residency** through the Employer Nomination Scheme (ENS) Subclass 186 visa after 3 years of employment with the same employer (under specific conditions).\n\n3.  **Labour Agreement stream:**\n    *   For employers who have a formal Labour Agreement with the Australian government. These agreements are negotiated to address specific labour shortages for a particular business or industry where standard visa programs are not suitable.\n    *   Visa duration and conditions are specified in the Labour Agreement.\n    *   Can also provide a pathway to permanent residency, as outlined in the Labour Agreement.\n\n---\n\n#### General Application Process:\n\nTypically involves three stages:\n\n1.  **Sponsorship application:** The employer applies to become a Standard Business Sponsor (if not already one).\n2.  **Nomination application:** The employer nominates a specific position for an overseas worker.\n3.  **Visa application:** The skilled worker applies for the 482 visa, linked to the approved nomination.\n\nThese applications can sometimes be lodged concurrently, or in sequence.\n\n---\n\n**Again, please remember to consult the official Department of Home Affairs website (homeaffairs.gov.au) or a registered migration agent for the most accurate and up-to-date information, as visa regulations are complex and subject to change.**',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-07 12:17:16',	0,	'2025-10-07 12:17:16',	0,	NULL),
