(320,	0,	30,	20251007,	'ai',	'Okay, I can provide you with information regarding the Subclass 186 Employer Nomination Scheme (ENS) visa for Australia.\n\nImportant Disclaimer: This information is for general guidance only. Visa rules and requirements can change frequently. You must always consult the official Australian Department of Home Affairs website (homeaffairs.gov.au) or a registered migration agent for the most accurate, up-to-date, and personalized advice.\n\nSubclass 186 Employer Nomination Scheme (ENS) Visa (Australia)\n\nThe Subclass 186 visa is a permanent resident visa that allows skilled workers, nominated by an Australian employer, to live and work in Australia permanently.\nPurpose & Key Feature\n\n   Permanent Residency: It\'s a direct pathway to Australian permanent residency.\n   Employer-Sponsored: Requires an eligible Australian employer to nominate you for a skilled position.\nStreams of the 186 Visa\n\nThere are three main streams:\nTemporary Residence Transition (TRT) stream: For applicants who currently hold a Subclass 457 or 482 visa and have worked for their nominating employer for a specified period (usually 2 or 3 years, depending on various factors and policy changes).\nDirect Entry (DE) stream: For applicants who are being nominated directly from offshore or who do not qualify for the TRT stream. This typically requires a skills assessment and more extensive work experience.\nLabour Agreement stream: For applicants nominated by an employer who has a formal Labour Agreement with the Australian government.\nKey Requirements (General)\n\nFor the Employer (Sponsor/Nominator):\n\n   Lawfully Operating Business: The business must be actively and lawfully operating in Australia.\n   Genuine Need: Demonstrate a genuine need for the nominated position.\n   Meet Nomination Requirements: This includes proving the position is full-time, ongoing, and meets Australian workplace standards and salary thresholds.\n   Training Levy (SAF): Pay the Skilling Australians Fund (SAF) levy at the time of nomination.\n   No Adverse Information: The business must have a satisfactory record of compliance with immigration and workplace laws.\n\nFor the Visa Applicant (Employee):\n\n   Age: Generally under 45 years old at the time of application (some exemptions apply, particularly for TRT stream or specific occupations/high-income earners).\n   English Language: Meet specified English language requirements (usually Competent English or higher).\n   Skills & Qualifications:\n       TRT Stream: Must hold a Subclass 457 or 482 visa and have worked for the employer in the nominated occupation for the required period. No separate skills assessment is usually required if transitioning from a 482 visa in the same occupation.\n       Direct Entry Stream: Requires a positive skills assessment for the nominated occupation from the relevant assessing authority. Must also have at least 3 years of relevant work experience (unless exempt).\n   Health & Character: Meet Australia\'s health and character requirements.\n   Occupation: Your occupation must be on the relevant skilled occupation list (MLTSSL or a specified list for the TRT stream).\nBenefits of the 186 Visa\n\n   Permanent Residency: Live and work permanently in Australia.\n   Medicare: Access to Australia\'s public healthcare scheme.\n   Education: Access to public education for dependent children.\n   Travel: Unlimited travel to and from Australia for 5 years.\n   Sponsorship: Potential to sponsor eligible relatives for permanent residency in the future (after a qualifying period).\n   Citizenship Pathway: A pathway to Australian citizenship after meeting residency requirements.\nApplication Process (General Steps)\n\nThe process typically involves two stages:\nNomination Application: The employer lodges a nomination application for the position and the applicant.\nVisa Application: The applicant lodges their visa application, usually concurrently or shortly after the nomination.\n\nBoth applications are assessed by the Department of Home Affairs.\nFees and Timelines\n\n   Application Fees (as of early 2024):\n       Visa application fee: AUD $4,805 for the main applicant, with additional fees for accompanying family members.\n       Employer Nomination (SAF Levy): Varies based on business turnover and visa duration (e.g., AUD $3,000 or $5,000 for a permanent visa).\n   Processing Times: Can vary significantly based on the stream, completeness of application, and current Departmental workload. Check the Department of Home Affairs website for current estimates.\n\nThe 186 visa is an excellent option for skilled professionals who have an Australian employer willing to sponsor them for permanent residency.',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-07 14:22:26',	0,	'2025-10-07 14:22:26',	0,	NULL),
(321,	0,	30,	20251007,	'member',	'tell me more',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-07 14:25:28',	0,	'2025-10-07 14:25:28',	0,	NULL),
(322,	0,	30,	20251007,	'ai',	'Okay, I will continue and provide more comprehensive information regarding the Subclass 186 Employer Nomination Scheme (ENS) visa for Australia. My apologies if the previous response was cut short.\n\nSubclass 186 Employer Nomination Scheme (ENS) Visa (Australia) - Continued\n\nAs mentioned, the Subclass 186 visa is a permanent resident visa that allows skilled workers, nominated by an Australian employer, to live and work in Australia permanently.\n\nKey Requirements (General)\n\nFor the Employer (Sponsor/Nominator):\n\n   Lawfully Operating Business: The business must be actively and lawfully operating in Australia.\n   Genuine Need: Demonstrate a genuine need for the nominated position within the business.\n   Meet Nomination Requirements: This includes proving the position is full-time, ongoing, and meets Australian workplace standards and salary thresholds. The terms and conditions of employment must be no less favourable than those provided to an Australian citizen or permanent resident for the same role, and the salary must meet the Annual Market Salary Rate (AMSR) and the Temporary Skilled Migration Income Threshold (TSMIT).\n   Training Levy (SAF): Pay the Skilling Australians Fund (SAF) levy at the time of nomination. This levy is based on the business\'s annual turnover and whether they are nominating a new position or extending an existing one. For permanent visas like the 186, it\'s a one-off payment:\n       Businesses with turnover less than AUD $10 million: AUD $3,000 per nomination.\n       Businesses with turnover greater than AUD $10 million: AUD $5,000 per nomination.\n\nFor the Visa Applicant (Employee):\n\n   Age: Generally, you must be under 45 years of age at the time of application, unless an exemption applies (e.g., certain high-income earners, medical practitioners, researchers, or those applying through the Labour Agreement stream with specific agreements).\n   Occupation: Your occupation must be on the relevant skilled occupation list for your chosen stream (MLTSSL for Direct Entry, or the relevant list for your Labour Agreement). For TRT, your occupation should be the same as your 457/482 visa.\n   Skills & Qualifications: You must have the skills and qualifications necessary to perform the duties of the nominated occupation. This varies significantly by stream:\n       Direct Entry (DE) Stream: Requires a positive skills assessment from the relevant assessing authority for your nominated occupation (unless exempt). You generally need at least 3 years of post-qualification full-time work experience in the nominated occupation.\n       Temporary Residence Transition (TRT) Stream: Typically does not require a new skills assessment if you already held a 457/482 visa in the same occupation. You must have worked for your nominating employer for a specified period (usually 2 or 3 years, depending on your 457/482 grant date and policy changes, in the nominated occupation while holding a 457 or 482 visa).\n       Labour Agreement Stream: Requirements are defined in the specific Labour Agreement.\n   English Language Proficiency: You must demonstrate \"competent English\" (e.g., IELTS score of at least 6.0 in each band, or equivalent in other approved tests like PTE, TOEFL iBT, OET, Cambridge C1 Advanced). Exemptions may apply for citizens of certain English-speaking countries.\n   Health and Character: All applicants and any accompanying family members must meet Australia\'s health and character requirements. You may need to undergo medical examinations and police checks.\n\nStreams of the 186 Visa (Detailed)\n\n1.  Temporary Residence Transition (TRT) stream:\n       Purpose: For skilled workers who already hold a Subclass 457 or 482 visa and have been working for their nominating employer.\n       Key Requirement: Generally, you must have worked full-time for your nominating employer in the nominated occupation for at least 2 years (for 457 visas granted before April 2017) or 3 years (for 482 visas, or 457 visas granted from April 2017 onwards) while holding a 457 or 482 visa. There are specific rules around the \"eligible period\" and \"grandfathering\" provisions.\n       Age: Must be under 45, unless exemptions apply.\n       Skills Assessment: Usually not required if you are transitioning from a 457/482.\n\n2.  Direct Entry (DE) stream:\n       Purpose: For applicants who are being nominated directly by an Australian employer, either from offshore or within Australia, and who do not qualify for the TRT stream.\n       Key Requirement: Requires a positive skills assessment in your nominated occupation, which must be on the Medium and Long-term Strategic Skills List (MLTSSL). You must also have at least 3 years of relevant work experience in your nominated occupation.\n       Age: Must be under 45, unless exemptions apply.\n       Labour Market Testing (LMT): The employer typically does not need to conduct LMT for the 186 DE nomination, unlike the 482 visa nomination. However, they must demonstrate a genuine need for the position.\n\n3.  Labour Agreement stream:\n       Purpose: For applicants nominated by an employer who has a formal Labour Agreement with the Australian government. These agreements are developed for specific industries or employers with demonstrated labour shortages that cannot be met by the Australian labour market.\n       Key Requirement: The specific criteria (e.g., age, English, skills, experience) are set out in the individual Labour Agreement. This stream offers flexibility from standard visa requirements.\n\nApplication Process (General Steps):\n\n1.  Employer Sponsorship: The employer must first be an approved Standard Business Sponsor (if they aren\'t already for a 482 visa).\n2.  Nomination Application: The employer lodges a nomination application for your position, pays the SAF levy, and demonstrates a genuine need.\n3.  Visa Application: You, as the applicant, then lodge your Subclass 186 visa application. This can be lodged concurrently with the nomination application, or after the nomination is approved.\n4.  Skills Assessment (DE Stream): If applying via the Direct Entry stream, you must have obtained a positive skills assessment before lodging your visa application.\n5.  Provide Documents: Supply all required documents (identity, qualifications, work experience, English test results, health insurance, etc.).\n6.  Health and Character Checks: Undertake any required medical examinations and provide police clearance certificates.\n7.  Decision: The Department of Home Affairs assesses both the nomination and the visa application.\n\nFees and Timelines:\n\n   Visa Application Charge (Base): AUD $4,805 (as of early 2024). Additional charges apply for each family member included in the application.\n   SAF Levy: AUD $3,000 or $5,000 paid by the employer.\n   Skills Assessment: Fees vary depending on the assessing authority.\n   Processing Times: Highly variable and can depend on the stream, completeness of the application, and current processing loads. They are often published on the Department of Home Affairs website and can range from several months to over a year.\n\nFamily Inclusion:\n\nYou can include eligible family members (spouse/partner and dependent children) in your Subclass 186 visa application. They will also be granted permanent residency.\n\nPathway to Citizenship:\n\nAfter holding a Subclass 186 permanent resident visa for a specified period (typically 4 years, with at least 12 months as a permanent resident, and meeting residency requirements), you may become eligible to apply for Australian citizenship.\n\nI hope this more detailed explanation provides you with a comprehensive understanding of the Subclass 186 visa. Do you have any further questions about this visa or perhaps other options?',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-07 14:25:28',	0,	'2025-10-07 14:25:28',	0,	NULL),
