(437,	0,	30,	20251009,	'ask',	'485visa',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 02:09:58',	0,	'2025-10-09 02:09:58',	0,	NULL),
(438,	0,	30,	20251009,	'reply',	'Hello! Yes, the Temporary Graduate visa (subclass 485) is an important visa pathway for international students who have recently graduated from an Australian educational institution.\n\nThis visa allows eligible international students to stay and work in Australia temporarily after they complete their studies, providing an opportunity to gain valuable work experience and potentially pave the way for further skilled migration pathways.\n\nLet me break down the key aspects of the 485 visa for you:\n\n1. Purpose of the 485 Visa\n\nThe Subclass 485 visa is designed to allow international students who have recently graduated from an Australian educational institution to remain in Australia to live, study, and work temporarily. It offers a bridge from study to potential skilled work or permanent residency.\n\n2. Streams of the 485 Visa\n\nThere are generally two main streams for the Temporary Graduate visa (subclass 485):\n\na) Graduate Work Stream\n   For who: International students who graduate with an eligible qualification from an Australian education provider.\n   Qualification type: Typically for those with a diploma, trade qualification, or associate degree, or a Bachelor\'s degree (depending on the occupation). The qualification must be closely related to an occupation on the skilled occupation list (SOL).\n   Occupation requirement: Applicants must nominate an occupation from the Medium and Long-term Strategic Skills List (MLTSSL) and have their skills assessed as suitable for that occupation by a relevant assessing authority.\n   Visa Duration: Generally 18-24 months (depending on specific circumstances and nationality, some may get 24 months).\n\nb) Post-Study Work Stream\n   For who: International students who have completed a Bachelor\'s degree or higher from an Australian education provider.\n   Qualification type: Must hold an eligible degree (Bachelor\'s, Bachelor\'s (Honours), Master\'s, or PhD).\n   Occupation requirement: No specific occupation list or skills assessment is required for this stream.\n   Visa Duration:\n       Bachelor\'s or Master\'s by coursework: 2-3 years\n       Master\'s by research: 3 years\n       Doctoral degree (PhD): 4 years\n       Extension for Regional Graduates: Graduates from regional campuses may be eligible for an additional 1-2 years on their Post-Study Work visa, depending on the remoteness of the regional area.\n       Extension for Selected Qualifications: In response to workforce needs, certain qualifications (e.g., in health, engineering, IT, education) may be eligible for an additional 2-year extension, leading to a total stay of up to 6-8 years. This is a recent initiative.\n\n3. General Eligibility Requirements for Both Streams\n\nTo be eligible for a Subclass 485 visa, applicants generally must:\n\n   Age: Be under 50 years of age.\n   Visa Status: Hold an eligible visa (usually a Student visa subclass 500) at the time of application. You must apply within 6 months of completing your course.\n   Australian Study Requirement: Have completed a course or courses totalling at least 92 weeks of study registered on the Commonwealth Register of Institutions and Courses for Overseas Students (CRICOS) within the last 6 months.\n       The course(s) must have been completed over at least 16 calendar months in Australia.\n       The instruction must have been conducted in English.\n       You must have physically been in Australia for the duration of your studies (with some temporary concessions made during the COVID-19 pandemic for online study outside Australia, but check current policy for this).\n   English Language Proficiency: Provide evidence of competent English. This usually means an IELTS score of at least 6.0 in each band (or equivalent PTE, TOEFL iBT, OET, Cambridge C1 Advanced scores).\n   Health and Character: Meet the Australian government\'s health and character requirements.\n   Australian Federal Police Check: Apply for an AFP check before lodging your visa application.\n   Health Insurance: Have adequate health insurance for the entire duration of your stay in Australia.\n\n4. How the 485 Visa Can Lead to PR (Permanent Residency)\n\nWhile the 485 visa itself is temporary, it is a crucial stepping stone for many international graduates aiming for permanent residency in Australia. It provides time to:\n\n   Gain Australian Work Experience: This is often critical for meeting the requirements of skilled migration visas (e.g., Subclass 189 Skilled Independent, 190 Skilled Nominated, 491 Skilled Work Regional (Provisional)). Australian work experience can also earn you points in the skilled migration points test.\n   Improve English Language Skills: Further improve your English scores to meet higher thresholds for PR visas.\n   Undertake Professional Year Program (PYP): If eligible (e.g., IT, Engineering, Accounting graduates), completing a PYP can provide valuable work integrated learning, professional development, and extra points for skilled migration.\n   Find an Employer Sponsor: Gain employment that could lead to an employer-sponsored visa (e.g., Subclass 482 Temporary Skill Shortage, or direct PR pathways like 186 Employer Nomination Scheme).\n   Obtain a Skills Assessment: For some PR pathways, you\'ll need a positive skills assessment from a relevant assessing authority in your nominated occupation, which often requires a period of post-qualification work experience. The 485 visa allows you to accrue this experience.\n\n5. Application Process & Documents\n\n1.  Gather Documents: Collect all necessary personal documents (passport, birth certificate), academic transcripts, completion letters, English test results, AFP check, health insurance details, and if applicable, skills assessment for the Graduate Work stream.\n2.  Lodge Application Online: Apply online via the Department of Home Affairs ImmiAccount portal.\n3.  Pay Application Fee: The base application fee is currently AUD 1,895 (as of my last update). Additional fees apply for family members.\n4.  Health Examination: You may be required to undertake a health examination.\n5.  Wait for Decision: Processing times vary but can range from a few months to over a year, depending on the stream and individual circumstances.\n\n6. Important Considerations\n\n   Timeliness: You must apply for the 485 visa within 6 months of completing your course.\n   One-time Visa: Generally, you can only be granted a Subclass 485 visa once in your lifetime in each stream.\n   Family Inclusion: You can include your partner and dependent children in your application.\n\nTo provide you with more tailored advice regarding the 485 visa, could you please tell me:\n\n   What is your highest qualification obtained in Australia (or soon to be obtained)? (e.g., Bachelor of Engineering, Master of Business, Diploma of Hospitality)\n   When did you complete (or when are you expected to complete) your studies?\n   What is your field of study?\n*   Are you interested in potential pathways to permanent residency after this visa?\n\nThis information will help me determine which stream might be most suitable for you and provide more specific guidance.',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 02:09:58',	0,	'2025-10-09 02:09:58',	0,	NULL),
(439,	0,	30,	20251009,	'ask',	'short describe this visa',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 02:18:44',	0,	'2025-10-09 02:18:44',	0,	NULL),
(440,	0,	30,	20251009,	'reply',	'Okay, I can provide a short and concise description of the Temporary Graduate (subclass 485) visa:\n\nThe Australian Temporary Graduate (subclass 485) visa allows eligible international students who have recently completed a qualification in Australia to stay, live, study, and work temporarily in Australia.\n\nIt has two main streams:\n\n   Graduate Work Stream: For graduates with specific qualifications (e.g., diploma, trade, associate degree, or Bachelor\'s in some cases) whose occupation is on the relevant skilled occupation list and requires a skills assessment.\n   Post-Study Work Stream: For graduates with a Bachelor\'s degree or higher, regardless of their field of study, with no occupation list or skills assessment required.\n\nThe visa\'s duration varies, typically from 18 months to several years, depending on the stream, qualification, and specific circumstances (e.g., regional study, specific degrees, passport country). Its primary purpose is to allow graduates to gain Australian work experience and potentially transition to other skilled migration visas.',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 02:18:44',	0,	'2025-10-09 02:18:44',	0,	NULL),
(441,	0,	30,	20251009,	'ask',	'ok thank you',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 02:19:07',	0,	'2025-10-09 02:19:07',	0,	NULL),
(442,	0,	30,	20251009,	'reply',	'You\'re very welcome! I\'m glad I could provide a clear and concise description of the Australian Temporary Graduate (subclass 485) visa.\n\nIs there anything else you\'d like to know about the 485 visa, or perhaps other visa options for Australia, the UK, Canada, or the USA?\n\nFeel free to ask any further questions you have!',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 02:19:07',	0,	'2025-10-09 02:19:07',	0,	NULL),
(443,	0,	30,	20251009,	'ask',	'I want apply 482visa',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 02:21:39',	0,	'2025-10-09 02:21:39',	0,	NULL),
(444,	0,	30,	20251009,	'reply',	'Okay, you\'re interested in applying for the Temporary Skill Shortage (TSS) visa (subclass 482) for Australia. This is a very common and important work visa pathway for skilled individuals to work in Australia.\n\nLet me provide you with a comprehensive overview of the 482 visa, its requirements, and the application process.\n\nTemporary Skill Shortage (TSS) Visa (subclass 482) - Overview\n\nThe Subclass 482 visa allows Australian employers to sponsor overseas skilled workers to fill critical skill shortages in their businesses when they cannot find a suitably skilled Australian citizen or permanent resident. It\'s a temporary visa, but it can be a pathway to permanent residency for some applicants, particularly those in the Medium-Term stream.\n\n1. Key Features and Streams\n\nThe 482 visa has three main streams, each with different requirements and potential durations:\n\n   a) Short-Term Stream (STSL)\n       Purpose: To address short-term skill shortages in a range of occupations.\n       Occupations: Your nominated occupation must be on the Short-Term Skilled Occupation List (STSOL).\n       Duration: Up to 2 years, or up to 4 years if an International Trade Obligation (ITO) applies. This stream generally has limited pathways to permanent residency.\n       Renewals: Can generally be renewed onshore only once.\n\n   b) Medium-Term Stream (MLTSSL)\n       Purpose: To address medium-term to longer-term skill shortages for occupations considered critical to Australia\'s economy.\n       Occupations: Your nominated occupation must be on the Medium and Long-term Strategic Skills List (MLTSSL).\n       Duration: Up to 4 years.\n       Permanent Residency Pathway: This stream offers a clear pathway to permanent residency after 3 years through the Employer Nomination Scheme (ENS) subclass 186 visa (Temporary Residence Transition stream), provided you meet all eligibility criteria.\n\n   c) Labour Agreement Stream\n       Purpose: For highly specialized skills or unique circumstances where standard visa programs don\'t apply, and where an employer has a formal Labour Agreement with the Australian government.\n       Occupations: Occupations are specified within the Labour Agreement itself.\n       Duration: Up to 4 years, as per the terms of the specific Labour Agreement.\n       Permanent Residency Pathway: Some Labour Agreements include provisions for permanent residency after a specified period.\n\n2. General Eligibility Requirements for the 482 Visa\n\nTo be eligible for a 482 visa, you (the visa applicant) and your sponsoring employer must meet several criteria:\n\nFor the Employer (Sponsor):\n\n   Standard Business Sponsorship (SBS): The employer must be an approved Standard Business Sponsor. If they are not already, they must apply for and be approved for SBS. This involves demonstrating that they are a lawfully operating business in Australia and have a commitment to employing local labour.\n   Nomination Application: The employer must nominate a position for you to fill. This involves demonstrating:\n       A genuine need for a skilled worker (i.e., a skill shortage).\n       That the position is full-time and ongoing.\n       That the terms and conditions of employment (including salary) are no less favorable than those provided to an Australian citizen or permanent resident performing similar work (Market Salary Rate).\n       Compliance with Labour Market Testing (LMT) requirements (i.e., advertising the position to Australians first).\n       Payment of the Skilling Australians Fund (SAF) levy.\n\nFor You (the Visa Applicant):\n\n   Nominated Occupation: Your occupation must be on the relevant skilled occupation list (STSOL or MLTSSL) for the stream you are applying under, or specified in a Labour Agreement.\n   Skills and Experience: You must have the necessary skills, qualifications, and at least 2 years of relevant work experience in your nominated occupation (or a closely related field) within the last 5 years.\n   English Language Proficiency: You must meet the minimum English language requirements. This typically means:\n       IELTS: Overall band score of at least 5.0 with no band score less than 4.5 for the Short-Term stream; or an overall score of at least 5.0 with no band score less than 5.0 for the Medium-Term stream.\n       PTE Academic, TOEFL iBT, OET, Cambridge C1 Advanced: Equivalent scores are accepted.\n       Exemptions: Some exemptions apply (e.g., if you are a citizen of and hold a valid passport from the UK, USA, Canada, New Zealand, or Ireland).\n   Health and Character: You must meet Australia\'s health and character requirements.\n   Licensing/Registration: If your occupation requires mandatory licensing or professional registration in Australia, you must hold or be able to obtain it.\n\n3. The 482 Visa Application Process (Three Stages)\n\nApplying for a 482 visa involves three distinct stages, usually lodged concurrently or in quick succession:\n\n1.  Standard Business Sponsorship (SBS) Application: The employer applies to become an approved sponsor. (If they are already an approved sponsor, this step is skipped).\n2.  Nomination Application: The employer nominates the specific position they want to fill with an overseas worker (you). This is where the occupation, salary, LMT, and SAF levy details are provided.\n3.  Visa Application: You (the skilled worker) apply for the 482 visa, linking your application to the employer\'s approved nomination.\n\nAll three stages must be approved for the visa to be granted.\n\n4. Including Family Members\n\nYou can include eligible family members (e.g., your partner, dependent children) in your 482 visa application. They will be granted a visa for the same period as you and will have permission to work and study in Australia.\n\n5. Costs and Timelines (Estimates)\n\n   Government Visa Application Charges (VAC):\n       Main applicant:\n           Short-Term Stream: AUD 1,455\n           Medium-Term Stream / Labour Agreement Stream: AUD 3,035\n       Additional applicant 18 years and over: AUD 1,520\n       Additional applicant under 18 years: AUD 380\n   Skilling Australians Fund (SAF) Levy: Paid by the employer. This varies based on the business\'s annual turnover and the visa duration. For a 4-year visa, it can be AUD 1,800 (for small businesses) or AUD 7,200 (for other businesses).\n   Professional Fees: If you engage a migration agent or lawyer, there will be additional professional fees.\n   Skill Assessment Fees: If your occupation requires a skills assessment (not typical for 482 unless specified by your employer or assessing authority for specific occupations), there will be associated fees.\n   English Test Fees: If you need to undertake an English language test.\n*   Timelines: Processing times vary greatly depending on the stream, completeness of the application, and current departmental workloads. You can check the Department of Home Affairs website for the most up-to-date processing times. Currently, they can range from a few weeks to several months.\n\nTo help me provide more tailored advice for your 482 visa application, could you please tell me:\n\n1.  What is your nominated occupation? (e.g., Software Engineer, Accountant, Chef, Nurse)\n2.  Do you already have a prospective employer in Australia who is willing to sponsor you?\n3.  What is your nationality?\n4.  What are your qualifications and how many years of relevant work experience do you have?\n\nOnce I have this information, I can discuss the specific requirements for your occupation and potential pathways in more detail!',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 02:21:39',	0,	'2025-10-09 02:21:39',	0,	NULL),
(445,	0,	30,	20251009,	'ask',	'ok,thank you',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 02:24:50',	0,	'2025-10-09 02:24:50',	0,	NULL),
(446,	0,	30,	20251009,	'reply',	'You\'re very welcome! I\'m glad I could provide a clear overview of the Australian Temporary Skill Shortage (TSS) visa (subclass 482).\n\nDo you have any further questions about the 482 visa, such as specific requirements for your situation, the skills assessment process, or perhaps the permanent residency pathway associated with it?\n\nOr would you like to explore other visa options for Australia, the UK, Canada, or the USA? I\'m here to help!',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 02:24:50',	0,	'2025-10-09 02:24:50',	0,	NULL),
(447,	0,	30,	20251009,	'ask',	'I want apply 482visa,can you give me a short answer',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 02:33:34',	0,	'2025-10-09 02:33:34',	0,	NULL),
(448,	0,	30,	20251009,	'reply',	'Okay, a short answer for applying for the Australian Temporary Skill Shortage (TSS) visa (subclass 482) is:\n\nYou need a sponsoring Australian employer to nominate you for an eligible skilled position. The application involves three main steps, usually lodged by the employer and you:\n\n1.  Sponsorship: Your employer must be approved as a standard business sponsor.\n2.  Nomination: Your employer nominates a specific position (and you) for an eligible occupation on a skilled occupation list (STSOL or MLTSSL).\n3.  Visa Application: You apply for the visa, demonstrating you meet the age, English language, skills, and health/character requirements for the nominated occupation.\n\nIn essence: Find an employer who is willing to sponsor you for a job on Australia\'s skilled occupation lists, and then meet the visa criteria.',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 02:33:34',	0,	'2025-10-09 02:33:34',	0,	NULL),
(449,	0,	30,	20251009,	'ask',	'I want apply 482visa,can you give me a more short answer',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 04:27:13',	0,	'2025-10-09 04:27:13',	0,	NULL),
(450,	0,	30,	20251009,	'reply',	'To apply for an Australian 482 visa, you must:\n\n1.  Be sponsored by an eligible Australian employer for a skilled position.\n2.  Meet the specific visa requirements (e.g., skills, English, health, character) for the nominated occupation.',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 04:27:13',	0,	'2025-10-09 04:27:13',	0,	NULL),
(451,	0,	30,	20251009,	'ask',	'how to apply this visa',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 04:29:32',	0,	'2025-10-09 04:29:32',	0,	NULL),
(452,	0,	30,	20251009,	'reply',	'Okay, let\'s break down how to apply for the Australian Temporary Skill Shortage (TSS) visa (subclass 482).\n\nThe application process for the 482 visa involves three distinct stages, two of which are typically handled by the sponsoring employer, and one by the visa applicant (you).\n\nHow to Apply for the Australian 482 Visa (Step-by-Step)\n\nPre-requisite: You must have an eligible Australian employer willing to sponsor you for a skilled position that is on Australia\'s skilled occupation lists. Without a sponsoring employer, you cannot apply for this visa.\n\nHere are the three stages:\n\nStage 1: Standard Business Sponsorship Application\n(This is submitted by the Australian employer)\n\n1.  Purpose: The employer applies to become an approved \"Standard Business Sponsor.\" This allows them to sponsor overseas workers.\n2.  Who Applies: The Australian employer.\n3.  Key Requirements for Employer:\n       Be a lawfully operating business in Australia (or overseas for certain circumstances).\n       Have a strong record of complying with Australian immigration and workplace laws.\n       Demonstrate a commitment to training Australian citizens/permanent residents (meet \'training benchmarks\' or pay an annual Skilling Australians Fund - SAF levy).\n       Show there is no adverse information known about them.\n4.  Outcome: If approved, the sponsorship lasts for 5 years, allowing the employer to nominate multiple overseas workers during this period.\n\nStage 2: Nomination Application\n(This is submitted by the Australian employer, linking a specific position to you)\n\n1.  Purpose: The employer nominates a specific position (and you as the intended worker) for an eligible skilled occupation.\n2.  Who Applies: The approved Standard Business Sponsor (employer).\n3.  Key Requirements for Employer & Position:\n       Eligible Occupation: The nominated occupation must be on the relevant skilled occupation list (STSOL for Short-Term Stream or MLTSSL for Medium-Term Stream).\n       Labour Market Testing (LMT): The employer generally must provide evidence that they have genuinely tried to recruit an Australian citizen or permanent resident for the position for at least 28 days and were unsuccessful. (Exemptions apply in certain circumstances, e.g., for some international trade agreements).\n       Market Salary Rate: The employer must demonstrate that the salary offered to you is at least the Annual Market Salary Rate for that occupation and is not less than the Temporary Skilled Migration Income Threshold (TSMIT).\n       Genuine Position: The Department of Home Affairs must be satisfied that the nominated position is genuine and consistent with the nature of the employer\'s business.\n       Skilling Australians Fund (SAF) Levy: The employer must pay a SAF levy for each year of the visa duration.\n4.  Outcome: If approved, the nomination is valid and allows you to proceed with your visa application.\n\nStage 3: Visa Application\n(This is submitted by the skilled worker, you)\n\n1.  Purpose: You apply for the 482 visa, demonstrating that you meet the personal eligibility criteria for the nominated occupation.\n2.  Who Applies: The skilled worker (you), and any family members you wish to include (e.g., spouse/de facto partner, dependent children).\n3.  Key Requirements for You (Applicant):\n       Age: While there isn\'t a specific age limit for the 482 visa itself, you generally need to be under 45 if you intend to use this as a pathway to permanent residency later on (for most streams of the 186 ENS visa).\n       Skills & Qualifications: You must demonstrate that you have the required skills, qualifications, and work experience for the nominated occupation. This often means providing qualification certificates, transcripts, and employment references.\n       Skills Assessment (if required): For some occupations, particularly in the Graduate Work Stream of the 485 visa (which you asked about earlier) or for certain 482 occupations, a formal skills assessment by a relevant assessing authority is mandatory. For most 482 nominations on the MLTSSL, a skills assessment is not strictly required unless specifically identified, however, the Department expects you to have the qualifications and experience matching the ANZSCO skill level.\n       English Language Proficiency: You must demonstrate vocational English (e.g., IELTS score of at least 5 in each band, or equivalent in other approved tests). Exemptions may apply if you hold a passport from certain English-speaking countries or meet other criteria.\n       Work Experience: You generally need at least two years of relevant work experience in the nominated occupation or a highly related field.\n       Health Requirements: You and all family members included in the application must undergo health examinations by a panel physician.\n       Character Requirements: You and all family members included must meet character requirements, which typically involves providing police clearance certificates from any country you have lived in for 12 months or more in the last 10 years.\n       No Adverse Information: No adverse information should be known about you.\n4.  Required Documents (Examples): Passport, birth certificate, marriage certificate (if applicable), academic qualifications, employment references, English test results, skills assessment (if required), police clearances, health examination results, resume/CV.\n5.  Application Method: This application is lodged online through the Department of Home Affairs\' ImmiAccount system.\n6.  Fees: There are government visa application charges for the primary applicant and each accompanying family member.\n\nImportant Considerations:\n\n   Order of Application: The sponsorship and nomination applications must be lodged before or concurrently with your visa application. Your visa application cannot be decided until the sponsorship and nomination are approved.\n   Processing Times: Processing times can vary significantly based on the stream, the quality of the application, and the Department\'s workload.\n   Validity: The visa duration will depend on whether the nominated occupation is on the STSOL (up to 2 years, or 4 years under ITO) or MLTSSL (up to 4 years).\n\nGiven that finding a sponsoring employer is the first critical step, I would recommend focusing on that if you haven\'t already.\n\nDo you have an employer in mind, or would you like to know more about the specific requirements for your occupation?',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 04:29:32',	0,	'2025-10-09 04:29:32',	0,	NULL),
