(454,	0,	30,	20251009,	'reply',	'You\'re very welcome! I\'m glad I could provide a clear breakdown of the application process for the Australian Temporary Skill Shortage (TSS) visa (subclass 482).\n\nDo you have any further questions about any of these stages, such as specific requirements for your occupation, English language requirements, skills assessment, or the documents you\'ll need?\n\nOr perhaps you\'d like to explore other visa pathways for Australia, the UK, Canada, or the USA? I\'m here to help with any migration-related queries you might have!',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 04:33:56',	0,	'2025-10-09 04:33:56',	0,	NULL),
(455,	0,	30,	20251009,	'ask',	'Do I meet the requirements to apply for this visa?',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 04:35:14',	0,	'2025-10-09 04:35:14',	0,	NULL),
(456,	0,	30,	20251009,	'reply',	'That\'s an excellent and crucial question! To determine if you meet the requirements for the Temporary Skill Shortage (TSS) visa (subclass 482), I need to understand your specific situation.\n\nThe eligibility for a 482 visa is highly individual and depends on several factors related to you (the visa applicant) and the job/employer (the nomination).\n\nTo give you a proper assessment, please provide me with the following key information:\n\nAbout You (The Visa Applicant):\n\n1.  Nationality/Citizenship: Which country are you a citizen of?\n2.  Age: (While there\'s no age limit for the 482 visa, it helps for context).\n3.  Education:\n       What is your highest level of education (e.g., Bachelor\'s Degree, Master\'s Degree, Diploma, Trade Qualification)?\n       What field of study was it in?\n       Where did you obtain this qualification (country and institution)?\n4.  Work Experience:\n       What is your current occupation or the occupation you wish to be sponsored for?\n       How many years of full-time work experience do you have in this occupation (or a closely related one)? Please specify dates.\n       What were your main duties and responsibilities in this role?\n       Do you have any formal employment contracts, payslips, or reference letters to prove this experience?\n5.  English Language Proficiency:\n       Have you taken an English language test (e.g., IELTS, PTE Academic, TOEFL iBT, OET, Cambridge C1 Advanced)?\n       If yes, what were your scores for each component (Listening, Reading, Writing, Speaking) and when did you take the test?\n       If no, are you exempt from English language testing (e.g., citizen of certain countries like UK, USA, Canada, NZ, Ireland, or studied in English for 5+ years)?\n\nAbout the Job / Employer (If Known):\n\n1.  Sponsoring Employer: Do you currently have an Australian employer who is willing to sponsor you, or are you looking for one?\n2.  Nominated Occupation: What specific job title or occupation are they offering to sponsor you for?\n3.  Salary: What is the proposed annual salary for this position? (This needs to meet the Temporary Skilled Migration Income Threshold - TSMIT, currently AUD70,000, and the Annual Market Salary Rate).\n4.  Location: Where in Australia is the job located?\n\nOnce I have this information, I can provide a much more tailored assessment of your potential eligibility and what steps you would need to take.',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 04:35:14',	0,	'2025-10-09 04:35:14',	0,	NULL),
(457,	0,	30,	20251009,	'ask',	'Do I meet the requirements to apply for this visa?',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 04:38:49',	0,	'2025-10-09 04:38:49',	0,	NULL),
(458,	0,	30,	20251009,	'reply',	'That\'s the most important question to ask!\n\nHowever, as an AI, I cannot definitively determine if you meet the requirements without specific details about your individual situation. My previous response outlined the crucial information I need from you to assess your potential eligibility.\n\nThe 482 visa\'s requirements are very specific and depend heavily on:\n\n   Your qualifications and work experience (to match an eligible occupation).\n   Your nationality and English language ability.\n   The specific job offer and sponsoring employer.\n\nTo provide you with an accurate assessment of whether you might meet the requirements, please provide the information I requested earlier:\n\nAbout You (The Visa Applicant):\n\n1.  Nationality/Citizenship:\n2.  Age:\n3.  Education:\n       Highest qualification, field of study, country of institution.\n4.  Work Experience:\n       Current/nominated occupation.\n       Years of full-time experience in this role (dates, main duties).\n5.  English Language Proficiency:\n    *   Test scores (IELTS, PTE, etc.) and date, or reason for exemption.\n\nAbout the Job / Employer (If Known):\n\n1.  Sponsoring Employer: Do you have one, or are you looking?\n2.  Nominated Occupation: Specific job title.\n3.  Salary: Annual salary being offered.\n4.  Location: Where the job is based in Australia.\n\nOnce you provide these details, I can give you a much more tailored and informed assessment of your potential eligibility for the 482 visa.',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 04:38:49',	0,	'2025-10-09 04:38:49',	0,	NULL),
(459,	0,	30,	20251009,	'ask',	'ok,wait me a moment',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 04:39:46',	0,	'2025-10-09 04:39:46',	0,	NULL),
(460,	0,	30,	20251009,	'reply',	'Okay, I will wait for you to provide those details. Take your time!\n\nOnce you share the information about your background and the potential job/employer, I can give you a more accurate assessment of your potential eligibility for the Australian 482 visa.\n\nI\'m ready when you are.',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 04:39:46',	0,	'2025-10-09 04:39:46',	0,	NULL),
(461,	0,	30,	20251009,	'ask',	'study',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 04:57:17',	0,	'2025-10-09 04:57:17',	0,	NULL),
(462,	0,	30,	20251009,	'reply',	'Thank you for your input.\n\nCould you please clarify what you mean by \"study\"?\n\nAre you providing information about your educational background as part of the details I requested for assessing your eligibility for the 482 visa?\n\nOr are you now interested in exploring study visa options for Australia, the UK, Canada, or the USA?\n\nOnce you clarify, I can provide the most relevant information.\n\nIf it\'s for the 482 visa assessment, please provide:\n   Highest qualification: (e.g., Bachelor\'s Degree, Master\'s Degree, Diploma, Trade Qualification)\n   Field of study:\n*   Country and institution where you obtained this qualification.',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 04:57:17',	0,	'2025-10-09 04:57:17',	0,	NULL),
(463,	0,	30,	20251009,	'ask',	'visa',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 05:02:40',	0,	'2025-10-09 05:02:40',	0,	NULL),
(464,	0,	30,	20251009,	'reply',	'Thank you for clarifying!\n\nIt sounds like you are still focused on the 482 visa and are perhaps starting to provide the details of your \"study\" (education) and then wish to discuss \"visa\" options.\n\nPlease continue to provide the information I requested earlier so I can properly assess your potential eligibility for the Australian Temporary Skill Shortage (TSS) visa (subclass 482).\n\nRegarding your education (\"study\"), please provide:\n\n   Highest qualification: (e.g., Bachelor\'s Degree, Master\'s Degree, Diploma, Trade Qualification, etc.)\n   Field of study: (e.g., Electrical Engineering, Nursing, IT, Hospitality Management, etc.)\n*   Country and institution: Where did you obtain this qualification? (e.g., University of Sydney, Australia; XYZ College, India)\n\nOnce I have this and the other requested details (Nationality, Work Experience, English Language, and details about a potential job offer), I can give you a much more tailored assessment.',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 05:02:40',	0,	'2025-10-09 05:02:40',	0,	NULL),
(465,	0,	30,	20251009,	'ask',	'visa type of UK',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 05:09:25',	0,	'2025-10-09 05:09:25',	0,	NULL),
(466,	0,	30,	20251009,	'reply',	'Okay, thank you for clarifying! It seems you\'d like to explore visa options for the United Kingdom now. I can certainly help with that.\n\nThe UK has a wide range of visa types, designed for various purposes such as working, studying, visiting, or joining family. To give you a comprehensive overview, I\'ll categorize them based on their primary purpose.\n\nUK Visa Types Overview\n\nHere are some of the main categories of UK visas:\n\n1. Work Visas (Skilled Worker Route)\n\nThis is the primary pathway for skilled individuals to come to the UK for work.\n\n   Skilled Worker visa:\n       Purpose: For skilled workers who have a job offer from an approved UK employer (who holds a sponsor licence).\n       Requirements:\n           Have a Certificate of Sponsorship from a licensed employer.\n           The job must be in an eligible skilled occupation list (with an appropriate SOC code).\n           Meet the minimum salary threshold for the job or the general threshold (£38,700 as of April 2024, though this can vary based on occupation, age, and other factors).\n           Meet English language requirements (B1 level on the Common European Framework of Reference for Languages - CEFR).\n           Proof of funds to support yourself, or your employer certifies maintenance.\n       Path to PR: This visa can lead to Indefinite Leave to Remain (ILR) after 5 years, subject to meeting specific criteria.\n\n   Health and Care Worker visa: A specific stream of the Skilled Worker visa for eligible health and social care professionals. It has lower application fees and an exemption from the Immigration Health Surcharge.\n\n   Global Business Mobility Visas: A suite of visas for overseas businesses to establish a presence in the UK, transfer staff, or for specific contract work. Includes Senior or Specialist Worker, Graduate Trainee, UK Expansion Worker, Service Supplier, and Secondment Worker.\n\n   Seasonal Worker visa: For specific temporary jobs in horticulture or poultry.\n\n2. Study Visas\n\nFor individuals wishing to pursue education in the UK.\n\n   Student visa (formerly Tier 4 General):\n       Purpose: For international students aged 16 and over coming to the UK to study at a licensed student sponsor (educational institution).\n       Requirements:\n           A Confirmation of Acceptance for Study (CAS) from a licensed UK educational institution.\n           Proof of funds to cover tuition fees and living costs.\n           Meet English language requirements (usually B2 level for degree-level study, B1 for below degree).\n           Show genuine intention to study.\n       Path to PR: Does not directly lead to PR, but successful graduates can switch to a Graduate visa or a Skilled Worker visa.\n\n   Child Student visa: For children aged 4-17 coming to the UK to study at an independent school.\n\n   Graduate visa:\n       Purpose: Allows international students who have successfully completed an eligible degree in the UK to stay and work, or look for work, for 2 years (3 years for PhD graduates) after graduation.\n       Requirements: Must have completed a degree from a UK Higher Education Provider with a track record of compliance. No sponsorship or specific job offer required. No English language test needed if you qualified for a Student visa.\n       Path to PR: Does not directly lead to PR, but allows time to find a sponsored job and switch to a Skilled Worker visa, which can lead to PR.\n\n3. Family Visas\n\nFor individuals joining family members who are already settled in the UK.\n\n   Partner/Spouse visa:\n       Purpose: For individuals to join their spouse, civil partner, or unmarried partner (who they\'ve lived with for at least 2 years) who is a British citizen, settled in the UK, or on a specific long-term visa.\n       Requirements:\n           Relationship must be genuine and subsisting.\n           Meet the financial requirement (currently £29,000 gross per year, increasing in stages).\n           Meet English language requirements (A1 level for initial application).\n           Adequate accommodation.\n       Path to PR: Leads to ILR after 5 years on this route.\n\n   Child visa: For children to join parents in the UK.\n\n   Parent of a British Child visa: For a parent to remain with their British child in the UK.\n\n4. Visit Visas\n\nFor short stays in the UK for tourism, business, or family visits.\n\n   Standard Visitor visa:\n       Purpose: For tourism, visiting family/friends, short-term business activities (e.g., attending meetings, conferences), short courses (up to 30 days), or private medical treatment.\n       Requirements:\n           Intend to leave the UK at the end of your visit.\n           Have sufficient funds to support yourself and your dependents.\n           Have funds to pay for your return or onward journey.\n       Duration: Typically up to 6 months.\n       Path to PR: Not possible. Visitors cannot switch to other visa categories from within the UK.\n\n5. Innovator and Entrepreneur Visas\n\nFor individuals looking to start or run innovative businesses in the UK.\n\n   Innovator Founder visa: For experienced businesspeople seeking to establish an innovative, viable, and scalable business in the UK (requires endorsement from an approved body). Can lead to ILR.\n*   Start-up visa: (Being phased out and replaced by Innovator Founder for most new applicants).\n\n6. Global Talent Visa\n\nFor leaders and potential leaders in academia or research, arts and culture, or digital technology. Requires an endorsement from an approved endorsing body. Can lead to ILR in 3-5 years.\n\nTo help me narrow down which UK visa might be most suitable for you, please tell me:\n\n1.  What is your primary goal for coming to the UK? (e.g., work, study, join family, visit, start a business)\n2.  What is your nationality?\n3.  Do you have any specific qualifications or work experience you\'d like to leverage?\n\nOnce I have this information, I can provide more focused guidance on the most relevant UK visa pathways for your situation.',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 05:09:25',	0,	'2025-10-09 05:09:25',	0,	NULL),
(467,	0,	30,	20251009,	'ask',	'visa type of USA',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 05:16:13',	0,	'2025-10-09 05:16:13',	0,	NULL),
(468,	0,	30,	20251009,	'reply',	'Okay, thank you for asking about USA visa types! The United States has a comprehensive and often complex visa system, broadly divided into two main categories: Nonimmigrant Visas (for temporary stays) and Immigrant Visas (for permanent residency, also known as Green Cards).\n\nHere’s an overview of the most common types:\n\nUSA Visa Types Overview\n\nA. Nonimmigrant Visas (for Temporary Stays)\n\nThese visas are for individuals coming to the U.S. for a specific purpose and a limited period. They do not directly lead to permanent residency, although some can be a stepping stone.\n\n1.  Work Visas:\n       H-1B Visa (Specialty Occupations):\n           Purpose: For highly skilled individuals in \"specialty occupations\" (requiring at least a bachelor\'s degree or its equivalent) to work for a U.S. employer. Common for IT, engineering, healthcare, finance.\n           Requirements: Job offer from a U.S. employer, employer-sponsored petition, usually requires a bachelor\'s degree in a specific field, and the job must be in a specialty occupation. Subject to an annual cap (lottery system for selection).\n           Duration: Up to 3 years, extendable to a maximum of 6 years.\n           Path to PR: Can be a stepping stone if the employer sponsors for an employment-based Green Card.\n       L-1 Visa (Intracompany Transferee):\n           Purpose: For employees of international companies to transfer to a U.S. office of the same company.\n           Requirements: Must have been employed by the foreign company for at least one year within the last three years in a managerial, executive (L-1A), or specialized knowledge capacity (L-1B).\n           Duration: Up to 7 years for L-1A, up to 5 years for L-1B.\n           Path to PR: L-1A (executives/managers) has a more direct path to an employment-based Green Card (EB-1C).\n       O-1 Visa (Individuals with Extraordinary Ability or Achievement):\n           Purpose: For individuals with extraordinary ability in the sciences, arts, education, business, or athletics, or extraordinary achievement in the motion picture or television industry.\n           Requirements: Extensive documentation of national or international acclaim in their field.\n           Duration: Initial stay up to 3 years, extendable in 1-year increments.\n           Path to PR: Often leads to an EB-1 Green Card (extraordinary ability).\n       TN Visa (NAFTA Professionals):\n           Purpose: For Canadian and Mexican citizens to work in specific professions listed under the USMCA (formerly NAFTA) agreement.\n           Requirements: Job offer in a listed profession, proof of professional qualifications (e.g., degree, license), Canadian or Mexican citizenship.\n           Duration: Up to 3 years, extendable indefinitely in 3-year increments as long as the job remains temporary.\n           Path to PR: Does not directly lead to PR, but individuals can pursue other immigrant visa options.\n       E-1/E-2 Visas (Treaty Traders/Investors):\n           Purpose: For nationals of countries with which the U.S. maintains treaties of commerce and navigation, to engage in substantial trade (E-1) or to develop and direct the operations of an enterprise in which they have invested a substantial amount of capital (E-2).\n           Requirements: Treaty nationality, substantial trade or investment, intent to depart the U.S. when the E status ends.\n           Duration: Initial stay up to 2 years, extendable in 2-year increments, as long as the treaty trade/investment activity continues.\n           Path to PR: Does not directly lead to PR.\n\n2.  Study Visas:\n       F-1 Visa (Academic Students):\n           Purpose: For full-time academic or language training programs at approved U.S. institutions.\n           Requirements: Acceptance from a SEVP-approved school (Form I-20), proof of sufficient funds to cover tuition and living expenses, intent to return to home country after studies.\n           Duration: For the duration of the academic program, plus Optional Practical Training (OPT) if eligible.\n           Path to PR: Does not directly lead to PR, but graduates may seek employer sponsorship for work visas (e.g., H-1B).\n       M-1 Visa (Vocational Students):\n           Purpose: For non-academic or vocational studies.\n           Requirements: Similar to F-1, but for vocational programs.\n           Duration: Limited to the length of the program, plus one month for every four months of study, not to exceed one year.\n\n3.  Visitor Visas:\n       B-1 Visa (Business Visitor):\n           Purpose: For temporary business activities like attending conferences, negotiating contracts, or consulting with business associates.\n       B-2 Visa (Tourist Visitor):\n           Purpose: For tourism, visiting friends/family, medical treatment, or participation in short recreational courses.\n       Requirements (B-1/B-2): Proof of funds, strong ties to home country, intent to depart U.S. after temporary stay.\n       Duration: Generally granted for up to 6 months per entry, though validity of visa sticker can be up to 10 years.\n\n4.  Exchange Visitor Visas (J-1):\n       Purpose: For participants in approved exchange programs, including students, scholars, trainees, interns, teachers, and specialists.\n       Requirements: Acceptance into a J-1 program (Form DS-2019), English proficiency, proof of funds.\n       Duration: Varies by program type. Some J-1 categories are subject to a \"two-year home-country physical presence requirement\" before adjusting status or applying for certain other visas.\n       Path to PR: Does not directly lead to PR, and the two-year rule can complicate pathways.\n\nB. Immigrant Visas (for Permanent Residency - Green Card)\n\nThese visas lead to lawful permanent resident status in the U.S., allowing you to live and work permanently.\n\n1.  Family-Based Immigrant Visas:\n       Purpose: For close family members of U.S. citizens or lawful permanent residents.\n       Categories:\n           Immediate Relatives (IR): Spouses, unmarried children under 21, and parents of U.S. citizens. No annual cap, generally faster processing.\n           Family Preference Categories (F): More distant relatives like adult children, married children, siblings of U.S. citizens, and spouses/unmarried children of Green Card holders. Subject to annual caps and lengthy waiting lists.\n       Requirements: Sponsorship by a U.S. citizen or Green Card holder, proof of relationship, financial sponsorship.\n\n2.  Employment-Based Immigrant Visas (EB):\n       Purpose: For foreign nationals who wish to immigrate to the U.S. based on their job skills.\n       Categories:\n           EB-1 (Priority Workers): Persons of extraordinary ability, outstanding professors/researchers, and multinational executives/managers. No PERM labor certification required, generally faster.\n           EB-2 (Professionals with Advanced Degrees or Exceptional Ability): Requires a master\'s degree or a bachelor\'s degree plus 5 years of progressive experience, or exceptional ability in the sciences, arts, or business. Requires PERM labor certification, unless eligible for a National Interest Waiver (NIW).\n           EB-3 (Skilled Workers, Professionals, and Other Workers): For skilled workers (requiring at least 2 years of training/experience), professionals (requiring a bachelor\'s degree), and \"other workers\" (unskilled labor). Requires PERM labor certification.\n           EB-4 (Special Immigrants): Includes certain religious workers, broadcasters, Iraqi/Afghan translators, and others.\n           EB-5 (Immigrant Investors): For individuals who invest a significant amount of capital (typically $1.05 million, or $8',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 05:16:13',	0,	'2025-10-09 05:16:13',	0,	NULL),
(469,	0,	30,	20251009,	'ask',	'visa type of AUS',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 05:19:37',	0,	'2025-10-09 05:19:37',	0,	NULL),
(470,	0,	30,	20251009,	'reply',	'Okay, let\'s look at the main visa types for Australia. Australia has a comprehensive immigration program, with visas broadly categorised based on their purpose: skilled work, family, study, business, and tourism.\n\nHere\'s an overview of the most common Australian visa types:\n\nAustralian Visa Types Overview\n\nA. Work Visas (Skilled Migration & Employer-Sponsored)\n\nThese visas are for individuals who want to work in Australia. They often require skills in demand, and many are pathways to permanent residency.\n\n1.  Skilled Migration Visas (Points-Tested)\n    These are popular options for skilled professionals who are not sponsored by an employer (initially) and meet specific criteria. They are points-tested based on factors like age, English proficiency, education, skilled employment, and Australian study.\n\n       Skilled Independent visa (subclass 189):\n           Purpose: For invited skilled workers who don\'t need sponsorship by an Australian employer, state, territory, or family member.\n           Requirements: Must be under 45, have an occupation on the Medium and Long-term Strategic Skills List (MLTSSL), a suitable skills assessment, competent English, and meet the points test pass mark.\n           Path to PR: Direct permanent residency.\n\n       Skilled Nominated visa (subclass 190):\n           Purpose: For invited skilled workers who are nominated by an Australian state or territory government.\n           Requirements: Similar to 189, but requires state/territory nomination. The occupation can be on either the MLTSSL or the Short-term Skilled Occupation List (STSOL) if specified by the nominating state/territory.\n           Path to PR: Direct permanent residency.\n\n       Skilled Work Regional (Provisional) visa (subclass 491):\n           Purpose: For invited skilled workers who are nominated by a state or territory government or sponsored by an eligible relative to live and work in regional Australia. It\'s a provisional visa.\n           Requirements: Similar to 189/190, but requires regional nomination/sponsorship and a commitment to live and work in a designated regional area.\n           Path to PR: Can lead to the Permanent Residence (Skilled Regional) visa (subclass 191) after 3 years, provided conditions (income, regional residence) are met.\n\n2.  Employer-Sponsored Visas\n    These visas require an Australian employer to sponsor you for a specific position.\n\n       Temporary Skill Shortage (TSS) visa (subclass 482):\n           Purpose: For skilled workers to come to Australia and work for an approved business that cannot find a suitably skilled Australian worker.\n           Requirements:\n               Sponsorship by an approved Australian employer.\n               Nominated occupation must be on the relevant skilled occupation list (STSOL or MLTSSL).\n               Relevant skills assessment (if required for your occupation/nationality).\n               Minimum of 2 years of relevant work experience.\n               English language proficiency.\n               Meet health and character requirements.\n           Path to PR: The Medium-Term Stream of the 482 visa can lead to the Employer Nomination Scheme (ENS) visa (subclass 186) after 2 or 3 years of working for the sponsor, depending on circumstances.\n\n       Employer Nomination Scheme (ENS) visa (subclass 186):\n           Purpose: For skilled workers nominated by an Australian employer to live and work in Australia permanently.\n           Requirements:\n               Sponsorship by an approved Australian employer.\n               Occupation on the MLTSSL.\n               Relevant skills assessment (unless exempt).\n               Usually 3 years of relevant work experience (unless exempt).\n               Under 45 years of age (unless exempt).\n               Competent English.\n               Can be applied for directly (Direct Entry Stream) or after holding a 482 visa (Temporary Residence Transition Stream).\n           Path to PR: Direct permanent residency.\n\n       Skilled Employer Sponsored Regional (Provisional) visa (subclass 494):\n           Purpose: For skilled workers nominated by an employer in regional Australia. It\'s a provisional visa.\n           Requirements: Similar to 186, but requires employer nomination in a designated regional area, a suitable skills assessment, and usually 3 years of work experience.\n           Path to PR: Can lead to the Permanent Residence (Skilled Regional) visa (subclass 191) after 3 years, provided conditions are met.\n\nB. Study Visas\n\n   Student visa (subclass 500):\n       Purpose: For international students to study full-time in Australia.\n       Requirements: Enrolment in a registered Australian course, Genuine Temporary Entrant (GTE) requirement, financial capacity, English proficiency, health insurance.\n       Path to PR: Does not directly lead to PR, but obtaining an Australian qualification and subsequent work experience can significantly improve eligibility for skilled migration visas (like 189, 190, 491).\n\n   Temporary Graduate visa (subclass 485):\n       Purpose: For international students who have recently graduated from an Australian educational institution to live, study, and work in Australia temporarily.\n       Requirements: Must have completed an eligible qualification in Australia, usually within 6 months of application, under 50 years of age. Has different streams (e.g., Post-Study Work, Graduate Work).\n       Path to PR: Does not directly lead to PR, but allows graduates to gain Australian work experience and potentially apply for skilled migration visas.\n\nC. Family Visas\n\nThese visas are for partners, children, parents, and other relatives of Australian citizens, permanent residents, or eligible New Zealand citizens.\n\n   Partner visas (subclass 820/801 onshore, 309/100 offshore):\n       Purpose: For individuals who are in a genuine de facto relationship or married to an Australian citizen, permanent resident, or eligible New Zealand citizen.\n       Requirements: Must provide extensive evidence of a genuine and continuing relationship.\n       Path to PR: Usually a two-stage process, with a temporary visa (820/309) granted first, leading to a permanent visa (801/100) after two years, provided the relationship continues.\n\n   Parent visas (e.g., subclass 103, 143):\n       Purpose: For parents of Australian citizens, permanent residents, or eligible New Zealand citizens to migrate to Australia.\n       Requirements: Meet the \'balance of family test\' (most children must live in Australia), sponsorship by an eligible child, health and character requirements. Contributory Parent visas (e.g., 143) have much higher application fees but faster processing times.\n       Path to PR: Direct permanent residency.\n\nD. Visitor Visas\n\n   Visitor visa (subclass 600):\n       Purpose: For tourism, visiting family/friends, or short-term business activities.\n       Requirements: Genuine intention to visit temporarily, sufficient funds, meet health and character requirements.\n    *   Path to PR: No.\n\nTo determine the most suitable Australian visa for you, I would need more details about your specific situation, particularly your skills, qualifications, work experience, English proficiency, and if you have any family links to Australia or an employer willing to sponsor you.',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 05:19:37',	0,	'2025-10-09 05:19:37',	0,	NULL),
