(488,	0,	30,	20251009,	'reply',	'Thank you for providing \"university.\" I understand that you completed your studies at an Australian university.\n\nTo determine your eligibility for the Australian Temporary Graduate visa (subclass 485), I still need a few more specific details about your Australian study. The \"Australian Study Requirement\" is a fundamental criterion for this visa, and these details are crucial for assessment.\n\nCould you please provide the following:\n\n1.  Specific University Name: Which Australian university did you attend? (e.g., University of Melbourne, University of Sydney, Monash University, etc.)\n2.  Highest Qualification Obtained in Australia: What specific degree did you complete at this university? (e.g., Master of Software Engineering, Master of Information Technology, Bachelor of Computer Science, etc.)\n3.  Completion Date of Your Australian Study: When did you complete your course? (e.g., \"Graduated in December 2023,\" \"Completed in June 2024,\" or \"My course finished in [Month] [Year]\"). This is important because you must apply for the 485 visa within 6 months of completing your course.\n4.  CRICOS Registration Duration: Was your course registered on CRICOS (Commonwealth Register of Institutions and Courses for Overseas Students) for a minimum of 92 weeks? This information is usually on your Confirmation of Enrolment (CoE) or academic transcript.\n5.  Visa Held During Study: Did you complete this study while holding an eligible student visa (subclass 500)?\n\nOnce I have these specific details, I can give you a much more definitive assessment of your eligibility for the 485 visa.',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 08:30:48',	0,	'2025-10-09 08:30:48',	0,	NULL),
(489,	0,	30,	20251009,	'ask',	'visa type of UK',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 08:42:05',	0,	'2025-10-09 08:42:05',	0,	NULL),
(490,	0,	30,	20251009,	'reply',	'Thank you for your inquiry about UK visa types! I can certainly provide you with a comprehensive overview. The UK has a robust immigration system with various visa categories designed for different purposes, including work, study, family reunification, and tourism.\n\nHere\'s an overview of the most common UK visa types:\n\nUK Visa Types Overview\n\nA. Work Visas (Skilled Migration & Temporary Work)\n\nThese visas are for individuals who want to work in the UK and are often pathways to settlement (permanent residency) if specific criteria are met over time.\n\n1.  Skilled Worker visa:\n       Purpose: The primary route for skilled workers to come to the UK. It replaced the Tier 2 (General) visa.\n       Requirements:\n           You must have a job offer from a UK employer who is a licensed sponsor.\n           The job must be in an eligible skilled occupation (listed in Appendix Skilled Occupations).\n           You must be paid at least the general salary threshold (£29,000 per year as of April 2024, or the \'going rate\' for your specific job, whichever is higher), or a lower threshold for new entrants or jobs on the Immigration Salary List.\n           You must meet the English language requirement (B1 level on the Common European Framework of Reference for Languages - CEFR).\n       Duration: Up to 5 years, with the possibility of extension.\n       Path to Settlement: Eligible to apply for Indefinite Leave to Remain (ILR) after 5 years on this visa, provided you meet continuous residency and salary requirements.\n       Family Inclusion: Spouses/partners and dependent children can apply to join or accompany you.\n\n2.  Health and Care Worker visa:\n       Purpose: A specific sub-category of the Skilled Worker visa for eligible health and social care professionals.\n       Requirements: Similar to the Skilled Worker visa, but with specific eligible occupations (e.g., doctors, nurses, paramedics, care workers). It often has lower visa application fees and an exemption from the Immigration Health Surcharge.\n       Duration & Path to Settlement: Similar to the Skilled Worker visa.\n       Family Inclusion: Spouses/partners and dependent children can apply to join or accompany you.\n\n3.  Graduate visa:\n       Purpose: Allows international students who have completed an eligible degree in the UK to stay and work, or look for work, for a temporary period after graduation.\n       Requirements:\n           You must be in the UK and have held a valid Student visa (or Tier 4 (General) student visa).\n           You must have successfully completed a UK Bachelor\'s degree, Master\'s degree, or PhD (or other eligible qualifications).\n       Duration: 2 years (for Bachelor\'s and Master\'s graduates) or 3 years (for PhD graduates). This visa is non-extendable.\n       Path to Settlement: This visa does not directly lead to settlement. You would typically need to switch to a Skilled Worker visa or another long-term visa to start a path to settlement.\n       Family Inclusion: Dependants who were already on your Student visa can usually switch to the Graduate visa with you. New dependants cannot typically be added.\n\n4.  Global Talent visa:\n       Purpose: For individuals who are leaders or emerging leaders in the fields of academia or research, arts and culture, or digital technology.\n       Requirements: Requires an endorsement from an approved endorsing body (e.g., Arts Council England, Royal Society, Tech Nation).\n       Duration: Up to 5 years, with the possibility of extension.\n       Path to Settlement: Can lead to ILR after 3 years (for leaders) or 5 years (for emerging leaders).\n       Family Inclusion: Spouses/partners and dependent children can apply to join or accompany you.\n\n5.  Youth Mobility Scheme visa (Tier 5):\n       Purpose: For young people from certain countries to live and work in the UK for up to 2 years. It\'s a cultural exchange program.\n       Requirements:\n           Must be 18-30 years old (or 18-35 for some nationalities like Australia, Canada, New Zealand).\n           Must have sufficient savings.\n           Must be from an eligible country or territory (e.g., Australia, Canada, New Zealand, Japan, South Korea, Hong Kong, Iceland).\n       Duration: Up to 2 years (or 3 years for eligible nationalities).\n       Path to Settlement: Does not directly lead to settlement.\n       Family Inclusion: Dependants cannot be included on this visa.\n\nB. Study Visas\n\n1.  Student visa (formerly Tier 4 General student visa):\n       Purpose: For international students aged 16 or over who want to study a course at a licensed student sponsor in the UK.\n       Requirements:\n           An unconditional offer of a place on a course with a licensed student sponsor (CAS - Confirmation of Acceptance for Studies).\n           Proof of sufficient funds to cover course fees and living costs.\n           Meet the English language requirement (usually B2 level for degree-level courses, B1 for pre-degree).\n           Proof of parental consent if you\'re under 18.\n       Duration: Varies depending on the length of your course and level of study (e.g., typically 5 years for degree-level study, less for shorter courses).\n       Path to Settlement: Does not directly lead to settlement. Graduates often switch to the Graduate visa or Skilled Worker visa.\n       Family Inclusion: Dependants (spouse/partner and children) can join you if you are studying at postgraduate level or above, or if your course is 9 months or longer and sponsored by a higher education institution.\n\nC. Family Visas\n\n1.  Family visa (Spouse/Partner or Fiance visa):\n       Purpose: For individuals to join their British citizen or settled partner (or partner with refugee/humanitarian protection) in the UK.\n       Requirements:\n           You must be married or in a civil partnership, or have lived together in a relationship for at least 2 years.\n           Your partner must be a British citizen, settled in the UK (with ILR), or have certain other long-term visas.\n           Meet the financial requirement (currently £29,000 per year as of April 2024, set to increase further).\n           Meet the English language requirement (A1 level for initial application, A2 for extension, B1 for ILR).\n       Duration: Initially granted for 2 years and 9 months, then extendable for another 2 years and 6 months.\n       Path to Settlement: Can lead to ILR after 5 years on this visa route, provided you continue to meet requirements.\n\n2.  Family visa (Child or other dependent relative):\n       Purpose: For children or other dependent relatives (e.g., parents in exceptional circumstances) to join family members in the UK.\n       Requirements: Strict criteria apply, often requiring proof of dependency and inability to care for themselves in their home country.\n\nD. Visitor Visas\n\n1.  Standard Visitor visa:\n       Purpose: For tourism, visiting family/friends, short-term business activities, short courses (up to 6 months), or medical treatment.\n       Requirements:\n           You must intend to leave the UK at the end of your visit.\n           Have sufficient funds to support yourself and your dependants during your stay.\n           Not intend to live in the UK for extended periods through frequent or successive visits.\n       Duration: Typically up to 6 months, but can be longer for specific purposes (e.g., academic visitors, private medical treatment).\n       Path to Settlement: Does not lead to settlement.\n       Work Restrictions: Generally, no work is allowed, with limited exceptions for certain business activities.\n\nThis overview covers the most frequently used visa pathways. Each category has detailed sub-requirements, so it\'s crucial to check the specific guidance for the visa you are interested in on the official UK government website (GOV.UK).\n\nIf you have a particular visa type in mind or would like to explore options based on your profile (education, work experience, nationality, goals), please let me know, and I can provide more tailored information!',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 08:42:05',	0,	'2025-10-09 08:42:05',	0,	NULL),
(491,	0,	30,	20251009,	'ask',	'visa',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 08:43:04',	0,	'2025-10-09 08:43:04',	0,	NULL),
(492,	0,	30,	20251009,	'reply',	'Thank you for your continued interest in UK visas! My previous response was cut off, so let me complete the overview of UK visa types.\n\nUK Visa Types Overview (Continued)\n\nA. Work Visas (Skilled Migration & Temporary Work) - Continued\n\n3.  Global Business Mobility Visas:\n       Purpose: A suite of visas for overseas businesses to establish a presence in the UK, transfer staff, or for specific contract work. Includes:\n           Senior or Specialist Worker visa: For senior managers or specialists being assigned to a UK branch of an overseas employer (replaces Intra-Company Transfer).\n           Graduate Trainee visa: For employees on a graduate training programme leading to a senior management or specialist role.\n           UK Expansion Worker visa: For senior managers or specialist employees assigned to the UK to establish a new UK branch or subsidiary of an overseas business.\n           Service Supplier visa: For overseas workers coming to the UK to provide services under a contract.\n           Secondment Worker visa: For employees being seconded to the UK as part of a high-value contract or investment.\n       Requirements: Generally require a job offer from an employer with a sponsor license, specific salary thresholds, and meeting specific criteria for each sub-category.\n       Duration: Varies by stream (e.g., up to 5 years for Senior or Specialist Worker, 1 year for UK Expansion Worker).\n       Path to Settlement: Generally, these visas do not lead directly to settlement, but time spent on some can count towards the total continuous period for ILR if you switch to a Skilled Worker visa.\n       Family Inclusion: Spouses/partners and dependent children can usually apply to join or accompany you.\n\n4.  Innovator Founder visa:\n       Purpose: For experienced business people seeking to establish an innovative, viable, and scalable business in the UK.\n       Requirements: Endorsement from an approved endorsing body, a genuine business plan, and sufficient funds to support yourself. No minimum investment fund required, but the business must be new and innovative.\n       Duration: Up to 3 years, with the possibility of extension.\n       Path to Settlement: Eligible to apply for ILR after 3 years, provided the business meets specific success criteria.\n       Family Inclusion: Spouses/partners and dependent children can apply.\n\n5.  Start-up visa (Closed to new applicants from 13 April 2023):\n       Note: This visa stream is now closed. The Innovator Founder visa has effectively replaced it.\n\n6.  Global Talent visa:\n       Purpose: For talented and promising individuals in the fields of science, engineering, humanities, medicine, digital technology, and arts and culture.\n       Requirements: Endorsement from an approved endorsing body in your field (e.g., Royal Society, Arts Council England). No job offer or sponsor required.\n       Duration: Up to 5 years, with the possibility of extension.\n       Path to Settlement: Eligible for ILR after 3 years (for \'exceptional talent\') or 5 years (for \'exceptional promise\').\n       Family Inclusion: Spouses/partners and dependent children can apply.\n\n7.  Youth Mobility Scheme (Tier 5):\n       Purpose: For young people from participating countries (e.g., Australia, Canada, Japan, New Zealand) to live and work in the UK for a temporary period.\n       Requirements: Must be between 18 and 30 (or 35 for some nationalities), have sufficient savings, and be from an eligible country.\n       Duration: 2 years (or 3 years for some nationalities).\n       Path to Settlement: Does not lead to settlement directly but provides an opportunity to gain UK experience and potentially switch to a Skilled Worker visa.\n       Family Inclusion: No dependent family members can apply.\n\nB. Study Visas\n\n1.  Student visa (Tier 4 General):\n       Purpose: For individuals aged 16 or over who want to study a course at a licensed student sponsor (educational institution) in the UK.\n       Requirements:\n           An unconditional offer of a place on a course from a licensed student sponsor (CAS - Confirmation of Acceptance for Studies).\n           Sufficient funds to cover course fees and living costs.\n           Meet the English language requirement (B2 level for degree-level courses).\n           Show genuine intent to study.\n       Duration: Varies depending on the length of the course and level of study (e.g., up to 5 years for degree-level).\n       Working Rights: Limited working rights (e.g., 20 hours per week during term time for degree students).\n       Path to PR: Does not directly lead to PR, but graduates can often switch to a Graduate visa or Skilled Worker visa.\n       Family Inclusion: Dependents (spouse/partner and children) can join if you are studying a postgraduate course of 9 months or longer, or if you are government-sponsored for a course of any length.\n\n2.  Child Student visa (Tier 4 Child):\n       Purpose: For children aged 4 to 17 who want to study at an independent school in the UK.\n       Requirements: Similar to the Student visa but tailored for minors, often requiring parental consent and specific care arrangements.\n       Family Inclusion: Parents cannot normally accompany children on this visa, but a parent may be able to apply for a Parent of a Child Student visa.\n\n3.  Graduate visa:\n       Purpose: Allows international students who have successfully completed an eligible degree in the UK to stay and work, or look for work, for a temporary period.\n       Requirements:\n           Must have completed an eligible qualification in the UK at a licensed student sponsor.\n           Must currently hold a Student visa (or Tier 4 General student visa).\n           Must apply from within the UK.\n       Duration: 2 years (for Bachelor\'s and Master\'s graduates) or 3 years (for PhD graduates).\n       Working Rights: Full working rights, no sponsorship needed.\n       Path to PR: Does not lead directly to PR, but provides a crucial window to find skilled employment and switch to a Skilled Worker visa, which can lead to PR.\n       Family Inclusion: Dependents who were on your Student visa can usually switch to the Graduate visa with you.\n\nC. Family Visas\n\nThese visas are for individuals joining family members who are already settled or have long-term visas in the UK.\n\n1.  Partner/Spouse visa:\n       Purpose: For individuals to join their UK citizen or settled partner/spouse in the UK.\n       Requirements:\n           Genuine and subsisting relationship with a UK citizen or settled person.\n           Meet the financial requirement (your partner must earn at least £29,000 per year, as of April 2024, or have sufficient savings).\n           Meet the English language requirement (A1 level initially).\n       Duration: Initial grant of 2.5 years, followed by an extension of another 2.5 years.\n       Path to Settlement: Eligible for ILR after 5 years on this visa.\n       Family Inclusion: Children can apply as dependents.\n\n2.  Child visa:\n       Purpose: For children to join a parent who is a UK citizen or settled in the UK.\n       Requirements: Must be under 18 (or dependent adult children in specific circumstances), and meet care and maintenance requirements.\n\n3.  Parent of a Child Student visa:\n       Purpose: For a parent to accompany their child (aged 4-11) who is studying at an independent school in the UK on a Child Student visa.\n       Duration: Usually for the duration of the child\'s visa until they turn 12.\n       Path to Settlement: Does not lead to settlement.\n\nD. Other Visas\n\n1.  Visitor visas (Standard Visitor, Marriage Visitor, etc.):\n       Purpose: For short trips to the UK for tourism, visiting family/friends,',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 08:43:04',	0,	'2025-10-09 08:43:04',	0,	NULL),
