(494,	0,	30,	20251009,	'reply',	'Thank you for providing \"study\" again. I understand you are likely trying to share information about your educational background in Australia to help assess your eligibility for the Australian Temporary Graduate visa (subclass 485).\n\nTo give you a definitive assessment for the 485 visa, the \"Australian Study Requirement\" is crucial, and I still need a few specific details about your completed Australian qualification.\n\nCould you please provide the following details about your Australian study:\n\n1.  Specific University Name: Which Australian university did you attend? (e.g., University of Melbourne, University of Sydney, Monash University, etc.)\n2.  Highest Qualification Obtained in Australia: What specific degree did you complete at this university? (e.g., Master of Software Engineering, Master of Information Technology, Bachelor of Computer Science, etc.)\n3.  Completion Date of Your Australian Study: When did you officially complete your course? (e.g., \"Graduated in December 2023,\" \"My course finished in June 2024,\" or \"My final results were released in [Month] [Year]\"). This is important because you must apply for the 485 visa within 6 months of completing your course.\n4.  CRICOS Registration Duration: Was your course registered on CRICOS (Commonwealth Register of Institutions and Courses for Overseas Students) for a minimum of 92 weeks? This information is usually found on your Confirmation of Enrolment (CoE) or academic transcript.\n5.  Visa Held During Study: Did you complete this study while holding an eligible student visa (subclass 500)?\n\nOnce I have these specific details, I can provide a much more accurate and definitive assessment of your eligibility for the Australian Temporary Graduate visa (subclass 485).',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-09 08:43:36',	0,	'2025-10-09 08:43:36',	0,	NULL),
(495,	0,	30,	20251010,	'ask',	'hi',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-10 00:00:45',	0,	'2025-10-10 00:00:45',	0,	NULL),
(496,	0,	30,	20251010,	'reply',	'Hello!\n\nI\'m ready to assist you further.\n\nWe were discussing your eligibility for the Australian Temporary Graduate visa (subclass 485). To give you a definitive assessment, I\'m still waiting for the specific details about your Australian study, which are crucial for the \"Australian Study Requirement.\"\n\nCould you please provide the following details:\n\n1.  Specific University Name: Which Australian university did you attend?\n2.  Highest Qualification Obtained in Australia: What specific degree did you complete at this university?\n3.  Completion Date of Your Australian Study: When did you officially complete your course?\n4.  CRICOS Registration Duration: Was your course registered on CRICOS for a minimum of 92 weeks?\n5.  Visa Held During Study: Did you complete this study while holding an eligible student visa (subclass 500)?\n\nAlternatively, if you have a different question or would like to discuss another topic (e.g., your initial query about employer sponsorship for Australia, or other countries like the UK, Canada, or USA), please let me know!\n\nI\'m here to help.',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-10 00:00:45',	0,	'2025-10-10 00:00:45',	0,	NULL),
(497,	0,	30,	20251010,	'ask',	'study',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-10 00:01:40',	0,	'2025-10-10 00:01:40',	0,	NULL),
(498,	0,	30,	20251010,	'reply',	'Thank you again for repeating \"study.\" I understand that you are focused on providing information related to your education to assess your eligibility for the Australian Temporary Graduate visa (subclass 485).\n\nThe details of your Australian study are absolutely critical for this visa, as the \"Australian Study Requirement\" is a core component.\n\nIt seems we might be going in circles a little with the detailed questions. Let\'s try to simplify. Could you please tell me:\n\n1.  Did you complete a Master\'s degree (or Bachelor\'s degree) at an Australian university?\n2.  When did you finish this degree? (e.g., \"last year,\" \"in 2023,\" \"a few months ago\")\n3.  Were you on a student visa (subclass 500) while studying in Australia?\n\nIf you can tell me just these three things, it will help me a great deal in determining your potential eligibility for the 485 visa.\n\nIf you don\'t have all the exact details right now, please just tell me what you remember.',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-10 00:01:40',	0,	'2025-10-10 00:01:40',	0,	NULL),
(499,	0,	30,	20251010,	'ask',	'visa',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-10 00:02:36',	0,	'2025-10-10 00:02:36',	0,	NULL),
(500,	0,	30,	20251010,	'reply',	'Thank you for providing \"visa.\"\n\nIt seems we are still trying to gather the specific details about your Australian study to finalize the assessment for the Australian Temporary Graduate visa (subclass 485). To help me understand if you meet the \"Australian Study Requirement\" for the 485 visa, could you please confirm:\n\n   Did you complete a Master\'s degree at an Australian university while on a student visa?\n   And when did you finish this Master\'s degree (e.g., within the last 6 months, last year, etc.)?\n\nYour answer to these simple questions will be very helpful.\n\nAlternatively, I noticed from your initial profile that your primary interest was in Australian employer sponsorship visas, and you have a job offer as a Software Engineer in Australia.\n\nIf you\'d like, we can shift our focus to assessing your eligibility for Australian Employer Sponsored visas (such as the Subclass 482 Temporary Skill Shortage visa or potentially a permanent employer sponsored visa), as this aligns with your stated goal and current job offer. This pathway is often more direct when you already have an employer willing to sponsor you.\n\nPlease let me know how you\'d like to proceed:\n\n1.  Provide the simplified study details for the 485 visa assessment.\n2.  Shift focus to Australian Employer Sponsorship visas.\n3.  Discuss visa options for another country (UK, Canada, USA).\n\nI\'m here to help with whichever pathway you\'d like to explore next!',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-10 00:02:36',	0,	'2025-10-10 00:02:36',	0,	NULL),
(501,	0,	30,	20251010,	'ask',	'syidy',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-10 00:05:31',	0,	'2025-10-10 00:05:31',	0,	NULL),
(502,	0,	30,	20251010,	'reply',	'Thank you for providing \"syidy.\" I understand you are likely still trying to communicate details about your studies in Australia.\n\nI appreciate your persistence, but it seems we are having some difficulty obtaining the specific details about your Australian study that are crucial for a definitive assessment of your eligibility for the Temporary Graduate visa (subclass 485). Without information such as the specific university, exact qualification (e.g., Master of Software Engineering), completion date, and confirmation of meeting the 92-week Australian Study Requirement while on a student visa, it\'s challenging to provide a conclusive assessment for the 485 visa.\n\nHowever, I recall from your initial profile that your primary interest for Australia is Employer Sponsorship Visas, and importantly, you have a job offer as a Software Engineer in Australia. This is a very strong and direct pathway to consider!\n\nGiven your situation, I recommend we prioritize evaluating the employer sponsorship/work visa pathway, as this aligns directly with your current job offer and stated goal. This is often the most practical and efficient route when you already have a sponsoring employer.\n\nLet\'s focus on the Australian Employer Sponsored Visa options for you as a Software Engineer with a job offer.\n\nAustralian Employer Sponsored Visa Pathways for a Software Engineer\n\nBased on your profile (Software Engineer, Master, Age 25-33, IELTS 7, >1 year work experience, job offer in Australia), the most relevant employer-sponsored visa options are:\n\n1.  Temporary Skill Shortage (TSS) visa (subclass 482)\n2.  Employer Nomination Scheme (ENS) visa (subclass 186) - Permanent\n\nLet\'s break these down:\n\n1. Temporary Skill Shortage (TSS) Visa (subclass 482)\n\nThis is the most common work visa for skilled individuals sponsored by an Australian employer. It allows you to live and work in Australia temporarily, and can often be a pathway to permanent residency.\n\n   Visa Type: Temporary Work Visa\n   Occupation: Software Engineer (ANZSCO 261313) is on the Medium and Long-term Strategic Skills List (MLTSSL), making it highly eligible for this visa.\n\nKey Requirements & Eligibility for You:\n\n   Sponsoring Employer: Your Australian employer must be an approved sponsor and nominate your position.\n   Occupation: Your nominated occupation is Software Engineer (ANZSCO 261313), which is eligible for the Medium-term stream of the 482 visa.\n   Skill Level:\n       Education: Your Master\'s degree is highly relevant.\n       Work Experience: You need at least 2 years of relevant work experience in your nominated occupation or a closely related field. Your profile states \"> 1 year\", so you will need to confirm if you have a full 2 years. This is a crucial point for eligibility. If you are slightly short, gaining more experience might be necessary before applying.\n   Skill Assessment: Generally, a formal skills assessment by the relevant assessing authority (for Software Engineer, this is usually ACS - Australian Computer Society) is NOT mandatory for the 482 visa if your qualifications and experience are straightforward. However, the Department of Home Affairs (DHA) or your employer might request one if there are doubts about your skills. For a 482 visa, the employer must be satisfied you meet the skill requirements.\n   English Language: You have an IELTS 7, which easily meets the \"Competent English\" requirement (IELTS 5.0 overall, with a minimum of 4.5 in each band).\n   Age: There is no age limit for the 482 visa.\n   Labour Market Testing (LMT): Your employer generally needs to demonstrate that they have attempted to recruit Australian citizens or permanent residents for the role before offering it to you. This involves advertising the position for a specific period.\n   Salary: Your salary must be at least the Annual Market Salary Rate (AMSR) for the occupation and no less than the Temporary Skilled Migration Income Threshold (TSMIT), which is currently AUD $70,000 per year (as of July 1, 2023).\n\nStreams:\n\n   Medium-term stream: As Software Engineer is on the MLTSSL, you would be eligible for this stream, which allows for a visa grant of up to 4 years.\n   Short-term stream: Not applicable to your occupation.\n   Labour Agreement stream: Not applicable unless your employer has a specific labour agreement.\n\nFamily Inclusion: You can include your partner and dependent children in your visa application.\n\nPath to Permanent Residency:\nAfter working for your sponsoring employer for 2 years on a 482 visa (under the Medium-term stream), you may become eligible for the Employer Nomination Scheme (ENS) visa (subclass 186) through the Temporary Residence Transition (TRT) stream. This is a direct pathway to Australian permanent residency.\n\n2. Employer Nomination Scheme (ENS) Visa (subclass 186) - Permanent\n\nThis is a permanent residency visa for skilled workers who are nominated by an Australian employer. There are two main streams relevant to you:\n\n   Occupation: Software Engineer (ANZSCO 261313) is eligible for this visa.\n\nA. Direct Entry (DE) stream:\nThis stream is for applicants who are nominated by an Australian employer and who have not recently held a 482 visa with that employer.\n\nKey Requirements & Eligibility for You (DE stream):\n\n   Sponsoring Employer: Your Australian employer must be an approved sponsor and nominate your position.\n   Occupation: Software Engineer (ANZSCO 261313).\n   Skill Assessment: A mandatory positive skills assessment from the relevant assessing authority (ACS for Software Engineer) is required for the Direct Entry stream. This is a significant difference from the 482 visa.\n       Action: You would need to apply for and obtain a positive ACS skills assessment. For ACS, a Master\'s degree in a relevant field typically requires 2 years of relevant work experience post-qualification to be deemed \'skilled\'. If your Master\'s is not in a closely related field, it could be more.\n   Work Experience: You need at least 3 years of relevant work experience in your nominated occupation. Your profile states \"> 1 year\", so you will need to confirm if you have a full 3 years. This is another crucial point for eligibility.\n   English Language: You have an IELTS 7, which meets the \"Competent English\" requirement (IELTS 6.0 overall, with a minimum of 5.0 in each band).\n   Age: You must be under 45 years of age at the time of application, unless an exemption applies. Your age (25-33) meets this requirement.\n   Salary: Your salary must meet the Annual Market Salary Rate (AMSR) for the occupation.\n\nB. Temporary Residence Transition (TRT) stream:\nThis stream is for applicants who have worked for their nominating employer for a certain period on a 482 visa.\n\nKey Requirements & Eligibility for You (TRT stream):\n\n*   Sponsoring Employer: Your Australian employer must be an approved sponsor and nominate your position',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-10 00:05:31',	0,	'2025-10-10 00:05:31',	0,	NULL),
(503,	0,	30,	20251010,	'ask',	'study',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-10 00:05:45',	0,	'2025-10-10 00:05:45',	0,	NULL),
(504,	0,	30,	20251010,	'reply',	'Thank you for providing \"study.\" I understand that your educational background, particularly your Master\'s degree, is a key part of your profile.\n\nWhile your Master\'s degree is a valuable asset for various migration pathways, and we previously explored the 485 Temporary Graduate visa (for which we still need specific Australian study details), let\'s now prioritize the Australian Employer Sponsored Visa pathways. This aligns with your initial profile information indicating a job offer in Australia as a Software Engineer and the system\'s directive to prioritize this route.\n\nYour Master\'s qualification and experience will be highly beneficial for these employer-sponsored visas.\n\nI had just begun explaining the Temporary Skill Shortage (TSS) visa (subclass 482). Let\'s continue with the detailed breakdown of this and other relevant employer-sponsored visas.\n\nAustralian Employer Sponsored Visa Pathways for a Software Engineer\n\nBased on your profile (Software Engineer, Master, Age 25-33, IELTS 7, >1 year work experience, job offer in Australia), the most relevant employer-sponsored visa options are:\n\n1.  Temporary Skill Shortage (TSS) visa (subclass 482)\n2.  Employer Nomination Scheme (ENS) visa (subclass 186) - Permanent\n\n1. Temporary Skill Shortage (TSS) Visa (subclass 482)\n\nThis is the most common work visa for skilled individuals sponsored by an Australian employer. It allows you to live and work in Australia temporarily, and can often be a pathway to permanent residency.\n\nVisa Type: Temporary Work Visa\n\nKey Requirements for You and Your Employer:\n\n   Occupation: Your occupation, \"Software Engineer\" (ANZSCO 261313), is on the Medium and Long-term Strategic Skills List (MLTSSL), making you eligible for the Medium-Term stream of the 482 visa.\n   Employer Sponsorship: Your employer must be a lawfully operating business in Australia and be approved as a standard business sponsor. They must nominate your position.\n   Genuine Position: The nominated position must be a genuine full-time position within the business and consistent with the nature of the business.\n   Labour Market Testing (LMT): The employer typically needs to demonstrate they have tested the Australian labour market (e.g., advertised the position for a specific period) to show no suitably qualified Australian worker is available. Exemptions can apply.\n   Salary: The salary offered must meet the Temporary Skilled Migration Income Threshold (TSMIT - currently AUD 70,000 per annum, as of July 1, 2023) and be no less than what an Australian would earn for performing the same role in the same location (Annual Market Salary Rate - AMSR).\n   Skills Assessment: For Software Engineers, a skills assessment is generally required for the 482 visa, particularly if the Department of Home Affairs requests one or if you intend to use this visa as a pathway to permanent residency (Subclass 186/189/190). The assessing authority for Software Engineer (ANZSCO 261313) is VETASSESS or ACS (Australian Computer Society).\n       ACS Assessment: As a Software Engineer, ACS is the most common and appropriate assessing body. They assess your educational qualifications and work experience to determine if they meet Australian standards.\n           Requirements: Generally, a Bachelor\'s degree or higher in a relevant field (like yours, a Master\'s) and relevant work experience. ACS will deduct years of experience based on your qualification\'s relevance. Given your Master\'s, they might require a minimum of 2 years of post-qualification experience, or more if your degree is not highly relevant. You mentioned \">1 year\" of experience, so you\'ll need to confirm if this meets ACS\'s specific deduction criteria.\n   English Language: You meet this with IELTS 7 (requirement is generally IELTS 5.0 overall, with no less than 4.5 in each component, or equivalent).\n   Work Experience: You need at least two years of relevant work experience for the 482 visa. You stated \">1 year,\" so please confirm if you have a full two years of post-qualification, full-time work experience in software engineering. This is a critical point.\n   Age: No age limit for the 482 visa.\n   Health and Character: You must meet the Australian health and character requirements.\n\nStreams:\n\n   Medium-Term Stream: Your occupation (Software Engineer) falls under this stream. This stream allows for a visa grant of up to four years.\n   Short-Term Stream: Not applicable to your occupation.\n\nPathway to Permanent Residency (PR):\n\n   After working for your sponsoring employer for two years on a 482 visa in the Medium-Term stream, you may be eligible to apply for the Employer Nomination Scheme (ENS) visa (subclass 186) - Temporary Residence Transition (TRT) stream. This is a direct pathway to PR.\n   You must continue to be employed in the nominated occupation and meet age, English, and other requirements at the time of PR application.\n\nFamily Inclusion:\n\n   You can include your spouse/partner and dependent children in your 482 visa application.\n\nApplication Steps:\n\n1.  Employer Sponsorship Application: Your employer applies to become an approved Standard Business Sponsor (if not already).\n2.  Nomination Application: Your employer nominates your position for the 482 visa.\n3.  Visa Application: You apply for the 482 visa, providing all required personal and skills documentation.\n4.  Skills Assessment (if required): You should initiate your ACS skills assessment as soon as possible, as it can take time. It\'s often beneficial to have this completed before the visa application is lodged, or at least be well underway.\n\nProcessing Times (based on publicly available information):\n\n   Sponsorship: 1-4 months\n   Nomination: 1-4 months\n   Visa (Medium-Term stream): 2-5 months (can vary significantly)\n\nFees (approximate, subject to change):\n\n   Sponsorship: AUD 420\n   Nomination: AUD 330\n   Visa Application: AUD 3,035 (main applicant) + AUD 3,035 (adult dependent) + AUD 760 (child dependent)\n   Skilling Australians Fund (SAF) Levy: Paid by employer, varies by business turnover and visa duration (e.g., AUD 1,200/year for small business, AUD 1,800/year for other businesses).\n\n2. Employer Nomination Scheme (ENS) Visa (subclass 186) - Permanent\n\nThis is a permanent visa for skilled workers who are nominated by an Australian employer. There are two main streams relevant to your situation:\n\na) Temporary Residence Transition (TRT) Stream:\n\n   Purpose: For 482 visa holders who have worked for their sponsoring employer for a specified period (currently 2 years). This is the most common PR pathway from the 482 visa.\n   Requirements (Key Differences from 482):\n       You must have held a 482 visa in the Medium-Term stream and worked for your nominating employer in the nominated occupation for at least two years.\n       Age: You must generally be under 45 years of age at the time of application (some exemptions apply, e.g., for high-income earners or specific occupations in regional areas).',	'immigration',	1,	0,	'2025-10-10 00:05:45',	0,	'2025-10-10 00:05:45',	0,	NULL),
